name: 1-methylpyrrolidine
Reason: The basic unit pyrrolidine has a melting point of -63 °C. The methyl group typically raises the melting point due to an increased Van der Waals forces as the molecular weight increases. However, in this case, the methyl group is able to donate electron density through an inductive effect to the adjacent nitrogen which can subtly reduce the overall dipole moment and thus may not have a pronounced effect on the melting point. Taking into account that a similar alkane, pentane (which lacks the ring structure and the nitrogen), has a melting point of -130 °C, the effect of the cyclic structure and the nitrogen should significantly raise it. Therefore, the introduction of the methyl group probably contributes to a slight increase of perhaps +3 °C from the baseline of the pyrrolidine.
